{"question": "What is DevOps?", "answer": "DevOps is a set of practices that combines software development (Dev) and IT operations (Ops) to shorten the development lifecycle and deliver high-quality software."},
{"question": "What are the benefits of DevOps?", "answer": "Faster delivery, improved collaboration, better quality, continuous integration/deployment, and automated processes."},
{"question": "What is CI/CD?", "answer": "CI/CD stands for Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment/Delivery, automating code integration, testing, and deployment."},
{"question": "What is Continuous Integration?", "answer": "Continuous Integration is the practice of merging code changes frequently into a central repository with automated testing."},
{"question": "What is Continuous Deployment?", "answer": "Continuous Deployment automatically deploys code changes to production after passing automated tests."},
{"question": "What is Continuous Delivery?", "answer": "Continuous Delivery ensures code is always in a deployable state, but deployment may be manual."},
{"question": "What is version control?", "answer": "Version control is a system that records changes to files over time, such as Git."},
{"question": "What is Git?", "answer": "Git is a distributed version control system for tracking code changes."},
{"question": "What is GitHub?", "answer": "GitHub is a cloud-based platform for hosting Git repositories and collaboration."},
{"question": "What is GitLab?", "answer": "GitLab is a DevOps platform for source code management, CI/CD, and collaboration."},
{"question": "What is Jenkins?", "answer": "Jenkins is an open-source automation server used for building, testing, and deploying code."},
{"question": "What is Ansible?", "answer": "Ansible is an open-source automation tool for configuration management, provisioning, and application deployment."},
{"question": "What is Puppet?", "answer": "Puppet is a configuration management tool for automating infrastructure management."},
{"question": "What is Chef?", "answer": "Chef is a configuration management tool that automates infrastructure using code."},
{"question": "What is Terraform?", "answer": "Terraform is an Infrastructure as Code (IaC) tool to provision and manage cloud resources."},
{"question": "What is Kubernetes?", "answer": "Kubernetes is an open-source container orchestration platform for automating deployment, scaling, and management of containers."},
{"question": "What is Docker?", "answer": "Docker is a platform to develop, ship, and run applications inside containers."},
{"question": "What is a container?", "answer": "A container is a lightweight, portable unit that packages an application and its dependencies together."},
{"question": "What is the difference between a virtual machine and a container?", "answer": "VMs virtualize hardware and run an OS per VM; containers share OS kernel and isolate apps, making them lightweight."},
{"question": "What is microservices architecture?", "answer": "Microservices architecture divides an application into small, loosely coupled services that can be developed and deployed independently."},
{"question": "What is monitoring in DevOps?", "answer": "Monitoring tracks application performance and infrastructure health to detect and fix issues."},
{"question": "What are the DevOps tools for monitoring?", "answer": "Prometheus, Nagios, Grafana, ELK Stack, and Datadog."},
{"question": "What is logging in DevOps?", "answer": "Logging collects and stores system and application logs for analysis and troubleshooting."},
{"question": "What is configuration management?", "answer": "Configuration management automates the setup, configuration, and maintenance of infrastructure and software."},
